    </div>
    <div class="prose-hm">
      <h2>What is a Harmonium</h2>
      <p>The harmonium is a free-reed keyboard instrument that produces sound by pushing air through small metal reeds. Unlike a piano which uses hammers and strings, the harmonium uses bellows — a folded air chamber. When you press a key a valve opens allowing air to flow through a specific reed, creating a sustained musical tone.</p>

      <h2>Parts of a Harmonium</h2>
      <p>The main parts are: Bellows (folded air chamber pumped by your left hand), Keyboard (white and black piano-style keys), Reeds (metal tongues tuned to specific pitches inside the body), Stops or Knobs (pull-out controls that activate different reed sets), Drone Stops (produce a continuous Sa note for accompaniment), and the Main Blow Knob that controls air flow to the keys.</p>

      <h2>Brief History in India</h2>
      <p>The harmonium was invented in Europe in the early 19th century and arrived in India during British colonial rule via Christian missionaries and schools. Indian classical musicians quickly adopted it because it holds a perfectly tuned drone note indefinitely — ideal for accompanying classical singing. Today harmonium is found in temples, concert halls, film studios, and homes across India.</p>

      <h2>How to Sit and Play</h2>
      <p>Sit cross-legged on the floor OR on a chair with the harmonium on a table at elbow height. Keep your back gently upright — not hunched. Your right hand plays the keys while your left hand pumps the bellows. Keep wrists level with the keyboard surface and use curved relaxed fingers with fingertips pressing keys.</p>

      <h2>Your First Sound — Play Sa</h2>
      <p>Sa is the tonic — the root note of Indian music. On our web harmonium: press the A key on your keyboard or tap the key labeled Sa. Hold it and listen to the sustained harmonium tone. This single note is the foundation of everything you will learn. Welcome to your harmonium journey.</p>

